  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is against the law in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prosecuted under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Violations can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines and lengthy prison sentences. Similarly, international agreements like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nBusinesses and financial institutions are also required to comply with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations, such as reporting suspicious transactions and verifying the identities of their customers. Failure to comply with these regulations can result in legal consequences for both individuals and organizations.",
